[[File:European Film Academy - European Film Awards logo.svg|thumb|right|[[European Film Academy]] Logo]] '''Cinema of Europe''' refers to the [[Film industry|film industries]] and [[film]]s produced in the continent of [[Europe]].
Europeans were the pioneers of the motion picture industry, with several innovative engineers and artists making an impact especially at the end of the 19th century. [[Louis Le Prince]] became famous for his 1888 [[Roundhay Garden Scene]], the first known celluloid film recorded. The [[Max Skladanowsky|Skladanowsky brothers]] from [[Berlin]] used their "Bioscop" to amaze the [[Berlin Wintergarten theatre|Wintergarten theatre]] audience with the first film show ever, from November 1 through 31, 1895. The [[Auguste and Louis Lumière|Lumière Brothers]] established the [[Cinematograph]]; which initiated the [[silent film]] era, a period where European cinema was a major commercial success. It remained so until the art-hostile environment of [[European theatre of World War II|World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Cinema Europe: The Other Hollywood| url= https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/188908/Cinema-Europe-The-Other-Hollywood-Part-1-Where-it-All-Began/overview| work= Rovi | publisher= The New York Times| accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref>
Notable European early film movements include [[German Expressionism]] (1920s), [[Soviet Montage]] (1920s), [[French Impressionist Cinema]] (1920s), [[Poetic realism]] (1930s), and [[Italian neorealism]] (1940s); it was a period now seen in retrospect as [[Cinema Europe: The Other Hollywood|"The Other Hollywood"]]. The first large-scale film studio was also established in Europe, with the [[Babelsberg Studio]] near Berlin in 1912.
Post [[World War II]] movements include [[Free Cinema]] (1950s), [[French New Wave]] (1950s&ndash;60s), [[Polish Film School]] (1950s&ndash;60s), [[Czechoslovak New Wave]] (1960s), [[New German Cinema]] (1960s&ndash;80s), [[British New Wave]] (1950s&ndash;60s), [[Spaghetti Western]] (1960s) and [[Cinema of Portugal#1960s|Novo Cinema]] (1960s&ndash;70s). The turn of the 21st century has seen movements such as [[Dogme 95]], [[New French Extremity]] and the [[Romanian New Wave]].
==History== [[File:Filmstudio Babelsberg Eingang.jpg|thumb|The [[Babelsberg Studio]] near [[Berlin]] was the first large-scale film studio in the world (founded 1912) and still produces international movies every year.]]
===19th century=== [[Auguste and Louis Lumière|Antoine Lumière]] realized, on 28 December 1895, the first projection, with the [[Cinematograph]], in Paris.<ref>[http://www.universalis.fr/encyclopedie/presentation-du-cinematographe-lumiere/ December 28, 1895.]</ref><ref>Georges Sadoul, ''Histoire du cinéma mondial, des origines à nos jours'', Flammarion, Paris, 1968, p. 19</ref><ref>[http://www.institut-lumiere.org/francais/patrimoinelumiere/premiereseance.html Institut Lumière.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105021719/http://www.institut-lumiere.org/francais/patrimoinelumiere/premiereseance.html |date=2014-01-05 }}</ref> In 1897, [[Georges Méliès]] established the first cinema studio on a rooftop property in [[Montreuil, Seine-Saint-Denis|Montreuil]], near Paris.
===20th century=== According to one study, "In the 1900s the European film industry was in good shape. European film companies pioneered both technological innovations such as projection, colour processes, and talking pictures, and content innovations such as the weekly newsreel, the cartoon, the serial, and the feature film. They held a large share of the US market, which at times reached 60 per cent. The French film companies were quick in setting up foreign production and distribution subsidiaries in European countries and the USA, and dominated international film distribution before the mid-1910s... By the early 1920s, all this had changed. The European film industry only held a marginal share of the US market, and a small share of its home markets. Most large European companies sold their foreign subsidiaries and exited from film production at home, while the emerging Hollywood studios built their foreign distribution networks."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bakker|first=Gerben|date=2005-05-01|title=The decline and fall of the European film industry: sunk costs, market size, and market structure, 1890–19271|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1468-0289.2005.00306.x/abstract|journal=The Economic History Review|language=en|volume=58|issue=2|pages=310–351|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0289.2005.00306.x|issn=1468-0289}}</ref>
The [[European Film Academy]] was founded in 1988 to celebrate European cinema through the [[European Film Awards]] annually.
Philippe Binant realised, on 2 February 2000, the first [[digital cinema]] projection in [[Europe]], with the DLP CINEMA technology developed by [[Texas Instruments]], in Paris.<ref>''[[Cahiers du cinéma]]'', n°hors-série, Paris, April 2000, p. 32 (''cf.'' also [http://academiecine.tv/files/8113/7674/5261/Histoire_communications.pdf ''Histoire des communications'', 2011, p. 10.]).</ref><ref>[http://motion.kodak.com/motion/uploadedFiles/FR_plugins_acrobat_fr_motion_action_actions29.pdf ''Cf.'' Binant, " Au cœur de la projection numérique ", ''Actions'', '''29''', Kodak, Paris, 2007, p. 12.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522233729/http://motion.kodak.com/motion/uploadedFiles/FR_plugins_acrobat_fr_motion_action_actions29.pdf |date=May 22, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=n_wTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT77&lpg=PT77#v=onepage&q=creton%20kitsopanidou%20binant Claude Forest, « De la pellicule aux pixels : l'anomie des exploitants de salles de cinéma », in Laurent Creton, Kira Kitsopanidou (sous la direction de), ''Les salles de cinéma : enjeux, défis et perspectives'', Armand Colin / Recherche, Paris, 2013, p. 116.]</ref>
Founded in 1992 with funding from the MEDIA programme [[Creative Europe]] and from the Centre national du cinéma et de l'image animée [[CNC, France]], Europa Cinemas is the first film theatre network focusing on European films. Its objective is to provide operational and financial support to cinemas that commit themselves to screen a significant number of European non-national films, to offer events and initiatives as well as promotional activities targeted at Young Audiences. Thanks to the support of [[Eurimages]] and the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the influence of Europa Cinemas extends to Eastern European countries, to the Balkans, to Russia and to Turkey. [[File:European at the cinema 1996-2016.png|thumb|261px|When Europeans go the cinema, what do they watch? (1996-2016)<ref name=europeans-cinema /> {{Legend|#73358d|US Films (56%)}} {{Legend|#9fcb4c|European films (25%)}} {{Legend|#3dbbd3|US/European co-productions (17%)}} {{Legend|#ff812b|Other films (2%)}}]] {{clarify|date=August 2018|text=Europa Cinemas in 2016: 41 countries, 644 cities, 1,078 cinemas, 2,648 screens MEDIA: 33 countries, 602 cities, 1,014 cinemas, 2,428 screens EURIMAGES: 3 countries, 37 cities, 58 cinemas, 205 screens MAE: 5 countries, 5 cities, 6 cinemas, 15 screens}}
Today [[Cinema of the United States|US productions]] dominate the European market. On average European films are distributed in only 2 or 3 countries; US productions in nearly 10.<ref>{{cite report |author= Christian Grece |date= May 2018|title=How do films circulate on VOD services and in cinemas in the European Union? |url= https://rm.coe.int/16807835be|publisher= European Audiovisual Observatory|page= 20 |access-date= 23 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bona |first1=Marzia |title=Europeans at the cinema, from East to West |url=https://www.europeandatajournalism.eu/eng/News/Data-news/Europeans-at-the-cinema-from-East-to-West |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=OBC Transeuropa/EDJNet |date=14 February 2018}}</ref> The top 10 most watched films in Europe between 1996 and 2016 were all US productions or co-productions. Excluding US productions the most watched movie in that period was ''[[The Intouchables]]'', a French production, like most of the other movies in the top 10.<ref name=europeans-cinema>{{cite news |last1=Comai |first1=Giorgio |title=Europeans at the cinema|url=https://www.europeandatajournalism.eu/eng/News/Data-news/Europeans-at-the-cinema |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=OBC Transeuropa/EDJNet|date=9 April 2018}}</ref> In 2016-2017 the only (partially) European film in the top ten of the most watched films in Europe was ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]''. Excluding it (which was a Netherlands, UK, France ''and US'' co-production<ref>{{cite web |title=Dunkirk |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/dunkirk |publisher=British Film Council |accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>) the European film with the best results was ''[[Paddington 2]]'', which sold 9.1 million tickets.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cebrián |first1=Sergio |title=European cinema regains ground |url=https://www.europeandatajournalism.eu/eng/News/Data-news/European-cinema-regains-ground |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=VoxEurop/EDJNet |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>
