[[File:Osterland 1250.PNG|thumb|right|Map of Osterland in the 13th century.]]

'''Osterland''' (''terra orientalis'') is a historical region in [[Germany]]. It was situated between the [[Elbe]] and [[Saale]] rivers to the north of [[Pleissnerland]] which it later absorbed and it included the city of [[Leipzig]]. The name derives from the previous name of the territory, ''[[Saxon Ostmark|Ostmark]]'', meaning "eastern [[marches|march]]."

Today, the area belongs to the German states of [[Thuringia]] and [[Saxony]].

