'''Robert Neil "Bob" DeArmond''' (September 29, 1911 &ndash; November 26, 2010)<ref name="bio">,DeArmond, R. N. [http://www.juneau.org/parkrec/museum/forms/digitalbob/bobbio.php Bob DeArmond Biography] Alaska State Library Historical Collections, February 2003</ref><ref name="died">{{cite web|url=http://www.juneau.org/parkrec/museum/forms/digitalbob/bobbio.php|title=Bob DeArmond Biography|work=Juneau-Douglas City Museum}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[historian]] who specialized in the [[history of Alaska]], especially the [[Alaska Panhandle]]. Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, DeArmond wrote several historical columns for southeast Alaska publications; these included ''Days of Yore'', ''Gastineau Bygones'', and ''News of the Gold Camp''. He lived in [[Sitka, Alaska]], and continued to write until his death.<ref name="digital">{{cite web |url=http://www.juneauempire.com/stories/050906/loc_20060509012.shtml |title="Digital Bob" |accessdate=2008-02-21 |last=Carroll |first=Tony |date=2006-05-09 |work=[[Juneau Empire]] |publisher=[[Morris Communications]]}}</ref>
==Early life== DeArmond was educated in Sitka and [[Tacoma, Washington]]; he graduated from [[Stadium High School]] in 1930. He worked in a [[salmon]] [[fish processing|cannery]] in the summer of 1930, and later received a reporting job for the ''[[Stroller's Weekly]]'' in [[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]]. In 1931, he traveled by [[rowboat]] from Sitka to Tacoma;<ref name="bio"/> DeArmond wrote a book about his travel, ''[[A Voyage in a Dory]]'', in 1999.<ref>[http://library.state.ak.us/hist/somebooks/some99.html Some Books About Alaska, 1999] Alaska Historical Library. May 25, 2005.</ref> He spent a year at the [[University of Oregon]].<ref name="bio"/> At age 15, he contributed a design for the [[flag of Alaska]] contest in 1927; it is housed in the [[Alaska State Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.juneauempire.com/stories/011801/Ent_MrClean.html |title="Mr. Clean of the museum world" |accessdate=2008-02-21 |last=Woodford |first=Riley |date=2001-01-18 |work=[[Juneau Empire]] |publisher=[[Morris Communications]]}}</ref>
==Professional life== DeArmond returned to Sitka after college. There, he worked in the fishing industry for 12 years. In 1938 he helped found the city of [[Pelican, Alaska]], where he served as a storekeeper and the [[postmaster]]. The DeArmond family moved to [[Ketchikan, Alaska]], in 1944, and Robert returned to journalism. He worked for the ''[[Ketchikan Daily News]]'', the ''[[Juneau Empire]]'' and other publications in covering the Alaska Territorial Legislature. DeArmond was a prolific history writer for regional publications. Over 700 of his columns were put in the online [[Digital Bob]] project,<ref name="bio"/> sponsored by the [[Juneau-Douglas City Museum]], beginning in 2004.<ref>[http://www.juneau.org/parkrec/museum/forms/digitalbob/bobabout.php A Few Words about the Project and Bob]. Juneau-Douglas City Museum.</ref>
DeArmond worked for territorial governor [[B. Frank Heintzleman]] in the 1950s and lived in [[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]] during this time.<ref name="bio"/>
==Family== He was married to artist [[Dale DeArmond]] née Burlison,<ref name="bio"/> who died on November 21, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.juneauempire.com/stories/112906/obi_20061129020.shtml |title="Dale DeArmond" |accessdate=2008-02-21 |date=2006-11-29 |work=[[Juneau Empire]] |publisher=[[Morris Communications]]}}</ref> They married in 1935 and had two children, William and Jane.<ref name="bio"/>
==Bibliography== *''The Founding of Juneau'' (1967) *(with Evangeline Atwood) ''Who's Who in Alaskan Politics'' (1977)
