{{merge to|Urmia|date=January 2018}}
[[File:Nestorian (Assyrian) Christian family making butter, Mawana, Persia.jpg|thumb|right|Nestorian ([[Assyrian people|Assyrian]]) Christian family making butter in Urmia Plain (Mawana), Persia, date unknown]]
'''Urmia Plain''' is a region in the [[West Azerbaijan Province]] of [[Iran]]. It lies between [[Lake Urmia]] to the east, and the Turkish border to the west.<ref>[http://www.a-gharbi.rmto.ir/NewSite/English/Include/ShowTab.asp?qsTab=1 TTO Provinces]</ref>

The inhabitants of the Urmia Plain are [[Azerbaijani people|Azerbaijanis]], in addition to some Kurds, Assyrians and Armenians, with the latter two having a historic presence in the region.<ref>{{cite book |author=Arianne Ishaya |title=Familiar Faces in Unfamiliar Places |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xo_iYXOR0EAC&pg=PA244 |date=7 October 2010 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=978-1-4535-6746-3 |pages=244–}}</ref>{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}<ref>{{cite book |author=Adam H. Becker |title=Revival and Awakening: American Evangelical Missionaries in Iran and the Origins of Assyrian Nationalism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WEGNBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA46 |date=2 March 2015 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=978-0-226-14531-0 |pages=46–}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=George David Malech |title=History of the Syrian Nation and the Old Evangelical-apostolic Church of the East: From Remote Antiquity to the Present Time |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6dLH1XD0clEC&pg=PR1 |year=1910 |publisher=Gorgias Press LLC |isbn=978-1-59333-408-6 |pages=1–}}</ref>

